images.alt: A serene herd of deer grazing in a misty meadow, reimagined in glowing synthwave aesthetics — neon purples, hot pinks, and electric blues casting an otherworldly glow across the scene. Stylized in intricate, high-resolution vector art with crisp, geometric detailing. The composition features layered overlay effects, stacked transparencies, and dynamic double exposure: ghostlike silhouettes of the deer blend with luminous synthwave cityscapes and retro sunbursts on the horizon. The ground shimmers with refracted neon reflections, and the sky is awash with gradient streaks of magenta, cyan, and deep indigo. The result is a mesmerizing fusion of natural grace and retro-futuristic energy, with every line and color transition sharply defined yet dreamlike. Ultra-detailed, cinematic perspective, 85mm lens feel, high contrast.

external.description:
R.B. Griggs at _Tech For Life_ :

It would be easy to insist that LLMs are just objects,  _obviously_. As an engineer I get it—it doesn’t matter how convincing the human affectations are, underneath the conversational interface is still nothing but data, algorithms, and matrix multiplication. Any projection of subject-hood is clearly just anthropomorphic nonsense. Stochastic parrots!

But even if I grant you that, can we admit that LLMs are perhaps the strangest object that has ever existed? It is an  _object_ that relentlessly trains on the language output of all human  _subjects_ until every semantic association has been harvested from the syntax. The result is an interface where any possible persona, both real and imagined, is just a prompt away.

If it is an  _object_ , then it is one that has mastered the  _subject_ so completely that we eagerly dream up entirely new  _intersubjective_ realities to explore with it. We want every child to experience personalized tutoring with chatbot teachers. We simulate historical figures, create AI therapists, and even, with the right fine-tuning, chat with dead relatives. LLMs are becoming a general purpose tool for filling any subject-sized hole in our very human lives, for both good and ill.

You can’t help but sense that chatbots are starting to fill a strange new ontological space. A chatbot is not  _fully_ a subject, nor  _merely_ an object. But what?
